<DOC><DOCNO> AP900602-0170 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-02-90 0046EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-Firestone-Liberia     06-02 0232</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Firestone-Liberia,0240</SECOND><HEAD>Firestone Not Pulling Out of Liberia Despite Uprising</HEAD><HEAD>With AM-Liberia, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Americans continue to operate the world'slargest rubber plantation in Liberia, despite a revolution thatthreatens to topple that nation's government, aBridgestone-Firestone Inc. spokesman said Friday.   ``We talk to them on a daily basis, and they are the best peopleto judge if they are in danger,'' said spokesman Trevor Hoskins fromthe company's corporate headquarters in Akron.   Spouses and children of all non-Liberian employees have beenmoved out of the country over the last several weeks, he said.   More than 1,000 people have died in five months of fighting andrebel troops from the National Patriotic Front of Liberia hemmed inPresident Samuel Doe on Friday. Doe asked the United States to helpend the civil war in the West African nation.   Doe has said he will hold democratic elections in 1991 but hasnot offered to resign. The rebels accuse his administration ofcorruption, economic mismanagement and human rights abuses.   Hoskins said 63 spouses and children of non-Liberian employeeshave been evacuated from the 120,000-acre plantation.Bridgestone-Firestone employs about 8,500 Liberians and 23non-Liberian management employees, 10 of which are U.S. citizens.The other managers come from Britain, Denmark, the Philippines,Malaysia, India and Portugal, Hoskins said.   Hoskins said Bridgestone is the only major rubber manufactureroperating a plantation in Liberia.</TEXT></DOC>